  "body": "## Simple Summary\r\nModify the positional and keyword arguments of `raw_call`:\r\n\r\n* make the 2nd positional argument (`data`) into a kwarg\r\n* add a new kwarg `method_id` that accepts a `Bytes[4]`, which is automatically prepended to `data` (minus the length)\r\n\r\n## Motivation\r\nThis simplifies the syntax of raw call while making it more powerful.\r\n\r\n* not requiring a data field simplifyies the syntax around simple ether transfers\r\n* accepting `method_id` as a separate argument makes for a stronger API and improves readability\r\n\r\n## Specification\r\nThe current syntax is:\r\n```python\r\n# sending ether\r\nraw_call(addr, b\"\", value=100)\r\n\r\n# erc20 transfer\r\nraw_call(\r\n    addr,\r\n    concat(method_id('transfer(address,uint256)'), convert(_to, bytes32), convert(100, bytes32))\r\n)\r\n```\r\n\r\nAfter implementing this VIP, the intended syntax:\r\n```python\r\n# sending ether\r\nraw_call(addr, value=100)\r\n\r\n# erc20 transfer\r\nraw_call(\r\n    addr,\r\n    method_id=method_id('transfer(address,uint256)'),\r\n    data=concat(convert(_to, bytes32), convert(100, bytes32))\r\n)\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Backwards Compatibility\r\nChanging `data` into a kwarg is a breaking change. We can add `method_id` as a kwarg immediately without breaking anything, and then convert `data` on the next breaking release.\r\n\r\n## Dependencies\r\nFor this to be maximally useful, we should first implement #1406 and #2098. The final goal is to be able to do something like this:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nraw_call(\r\n    addr,\r\n    method_id=ERC20.transfer.method_id,\r\n    data=abi.encode(_to, 100)\r\n)\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Copyright\r\nCopyright and related rights waived via [CC0](https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/)\r\n",
